<br>
/salute Eldratu<br>
/salute Kallisia<br>
<br>
Here is a not so short story about what happened. I tend to get gabby, but please bear with me. I WILL get to the point eventually heheh.<br>
<br>
I died to a DOT after gating to my bind point in the bank in FV. Felt dumb about it, and pretty sure I wasn't going to get a cleric to come res me. I hardly ever ask for a res, but I just hit 43 a few days ago (after 40 days played, I am not a powerleveler heh). Being one level from 44, I am now currently trying to grind out experience to get there. I hate doing that, and losing the experience on such a worthless sort of death was depressing.   <br>
<br>
I checked with Saga, and the highest cleric was 30. I never scoff at a res, but less than a 50 percent really wasn't worth the bother to the cleric to come all the way to my adopted home town. So I did what the truly desparate do. /who all cleric 34 60. Came up with too many names, so I cut it back to 39 60. Running down the list of names I looked for two things: race (I am a high elf), and location. There are many places on Norrath that I can return someone to very easily. <br>
<br>
I saw Eldratu in Great Divide. High elf, in a zone I can port to directly. Gave it a try, telling her I was dead in the bank in FV, not expecting anything but a &quot;sorry, busy&quot; even if she replied at all. She did reply, and said she was about to start a hunt. I think she was at a camp and set up. I was a little surprised that she explained so much of what she was doing, so I sent her a reply thanking her for replying and wishing her luck in her hunt. I started to peruse the list again and Eldratu said she was on the way to Firiona Vie to res me, coming via Butcherblock. I was surprised, and very happy. I sat and whined over /gu about my bad luck in dying so cheesily and forgot completely about offering her any money or whatever for coming to res me. <br>
<br>
She showed up with a druidess named Kallisia. As an amusing side note, Eldratu was wearing a robe and I, a wizard, was in chain mail. It really sort of made me chuckle. The game has evolved, eh? She res'd me, and I suddenly realized I better give her some money. Like I said, I hardly ever get a res and forget things like that. I gave her 100 platinum, all I had except for 2 gold 6 silver that I kept for beer money, and I would have given her alot more. The game is to the point for me where money and items mean diddly-squat, but I know clerics have to buy gems. I apologized for not having more and she said it was fine and thanked me for it. She and Kallisia left then and never once asked an embarassing question of how I happened to die in the bank *chuckle*.<br>
<br>
I still can't get over it. Call me cynical and pessimistic. These two took time out of their game play, with no promise of money or anything, and traveled clear across the world to help me. I have never met either, as far as I know, though Kallisia's name looks sorta familiar, and what they did was over and above the call of duty to a stranger. I never expected it, and it was a pleasant surprise in this dog-eat-dog phat lewt world. <br>
<br>
They are the kind of folks this server needs more of. Please, let us all try to emulate their example a bit more. It truly doesn't have to interfere with roleplay. I have scoffed at evil beings who ask me for aid and stomped off after giving them a stern warning, then sneakily OOC returned to assist (ack now my secret is out). I see no purpose in making the game harder for someone if I can aid them. I know the roleplay-heavy folks are going to throw rotten fruits at me for THAT one. <br>
<br>
At any rate, the kindness of Eldratu and Kallisia is a shining example to us, and I beg you to give them a kind word of greeting and perhaps a helping hand if they are in need someday. I would like to see reputation have a positive effect for once (points to the soapbox and shakes his head in disgust).<br>
<br>
Caladril<br>
